26 Sec. 2. Section 48-622.01, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025, is
27 amended to read:
28 48-622.01 There is hereby created in the state treasury a special
29 fund to be known as the State Unemployment Insurance Trust Fund. The fund
30 terminates on July 1, 2025, and the State Treasurer shall transfer any
31 money in the fund on such date to the Workforce Development Program Cash
-10-

LB1015 LB1015
2026 2026
1 Fund. Beginning July 1, 2025, all state unemployment insurance tax
2 collected under sections 48-648 to 48-661, less refunds, shall be paid
3 into the Workforce Development Program Cash Fund and the Business
4 Innovation Cash Fund.
5 Sec. 3. Section 48-648, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025, is
6 amended to read:
7 48-648 (1) With respect to wages for employment, combined tax shall
8 accrue and become payable by each employer not otherwise entitled to make
9 payments in lieu of contributions for each calendar year in which he or
10 she is subject to the Employment Security Law. Such combined tax shall
11 become due and be paid by each employer to the commissioner for the
12 Workforce Development Program Cash Fund, the Business Innovation Cash
13 Fund, and the Unemployment Trust Fund in such manner and at such times as
14 the commissioner may, by rule and regulation, prescribe. Such combined
15 tax shall not be deducted, in whole or in part, from the wages of
16 individuals in such employer's employ.
17 (2) The commissioner may require any employer whose annual payroll
18 for either of the two preceding calendar years has equaled or exceeded
19 one hundred thousand dollars to file combined tax returns and pay
20 combined taxes owed by an electronic method approved by the commissioner,
21 except when the employer establishes to the satisfaction of the
22 commissioner that filing the combined tax return or payment of the tax by
23 an electronic method would create a hardship for the employer.
24 (3) In the payment of any combined tax, a fractional part of a cent
25 shall be disregarded unless it amounts to one-half cent or more, in which
26 case it shall be increased to one cent. If the combined tax due for any
27 reporting period is less than five dollars, the employer need not remit
28 the combined tax.
29 (4) If two or more related corporations or limited liability
30 companies concurrently employ the same individual and compensate such
31 individual through a common paymaster which is one of such corporations
-11-

LB1015 LB1015
2026 2026
1 or limited liability companies, each such corporation or limited
2 liability company shall be considered to have paid as remuneration to
3 such individual only the amounts actually disbursed by it to such
4 individual and shall not be considered to have paid as remuneration to
5 such individual amounts actually disbursed to such individual by another
6 of such corporations or limited liability companies. An employee of a
7 wholly owned subsidiary shall be considered to be concurrently employed
8 by the parent corporation, company, or other entity and the wholly owned
9 subsidiary whether or not both companies separately provide remuneration.
10 (5) The professional employer organization shall report and pay
11 combined tax, penalties, and interest owed for wages earned by worksite
12 employees under the client's employer account number using the client's
13 combined tax rate. The client is liable for the payment of unpaid
14 combined tax, penalties, and interest owed for wages paid to worksite
15 employees, and the worksite employees shall be considered employees of
16 the client for purposes of the Employment Security Law.
17 (6) The Commissioner of Labor may require by rule and regulation
18 that each employer subject to the Employment Security Law shall submit to
19 the commissioner quarterly wage reports on such forms and in such manner
20 as the commissioner may prescribe. The commissioner may require any
21 employer whose annual payroll for either of the two preceding calendar
22 years has equaled or exceeded one hundred thousand dollars to file wage
23 reports by an electronic method approved by the commissioner, except when
24 the employer establishes to the satisfaction of the commissioner that
25 filing by an electronic method would create a hardship for the employer.
26 The quarterly wage reports shall be used by the commissioner to make
27 monetary determinations of claims for benefits.
28 Sec. 4. Section 48-649.01, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025, is
29 amended to read:
30 48-649.01 (1) By December 1 of each calendar year, the commissioner
31 shall determine the state unemployment insurance tax rate for the
-12-

LB1015 LB1015
2026 2026
1 following year based on information available through the department.
2 (2) If the state unemployment insurance tax rate is determined to be
3 zero percent pursuant to subsection (1) of this section, the contribution
4 rate for all employers shall equal one hundred percent of the combined
5 tax rate.
6 (3) If the state unemployment insurance tax rate is not zero percent
7 as determined in this section, the combined tax rate shall be divided so
8 that not less than eighty percent of the combined tax rate equals the
9 contribution rate and not more than twenty percent of the combined tax
10 rate equals the state unemployment insurance tax rate except for
11 employers who are assigned a combined tax rate of five and four-tenths
12 percent or more. For those employers, the state unemployment insurance
13 tax rate shall equal zero and their combined tax rate shall equal their
14 contribution rate.
15 (4) On or before December 31 of each calendar year, the commissioner
16 shall designate the percentage and proportion of the state unemployment
17 insurance tax rate that shall be remitted to the Workforce Development
18 Program Cash Fund for the support of workforce development programs and
19 to the Business Innovation Cash Fund for the support of workforce
20 innovation programs. The department shall execute a memorandum of
21 understanding with the Department of Economic Development before
22 September 30 of each calendar year to ensure the commissioner receives
23 sufficient information regarding the current status of programs
24 administered under the Business Innovation Act, including any data
25 necessary for the commissioner to make an informed determination pursuant
26 to this section.
